    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>NBC Limits Action For Human Interest</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steve Drake letter questions why NBC feels need to focus on human interest stories rather than more fully covering Olympic events themselves</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Ah, the Olympic Games. Something I look forward to every four years.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Ah, the Olympic Games. Something I look forward to every four years.</p>
        <p>Then I sit down and am quickly reminded of how it's covered by NBC. We're shown five minutes of an event and five minutes of how Bob or Sally trains or goes to school, etc. Do we really care about that? Didn't I tune in to see someone lift 300 pounds over his head or swim across shark-infested waters? Are the events so boring to NBC that they feel they need to bring them to life by adding all that human interest stuff, or are the competitors spaced that far apart that NBC needs to fill the time with something?</p>
        <p>I feel sorry for those who don't have access to MSNBC, CNBC and Canadian broadcasting. This is one man who's living up to our image with a remote!</p>
        <p>STEVE DRAKE  Seattle</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
